    "$$\\newcommand{\\ket}[1]{\\left|{#1}\\right\\rangle}$$\n",
    "$$\\newcommand{\\bra}[1]{\\left\\langle{#1}\\right|}$$\n",
    "### QOSF Mentorship Screening Task 3\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Kaelyn Ferris\n",
    "\n",
    "Learning by doing: the best way to understand the basics of quantum computation is to implement a quantum circuit simulator. This task is suitable both for people from computer sciences who want to learn about quantum computing, and for people from math/physics who want to exercise coding.\n",
    "\n",
    "Detailed description of the task with some learning resources and examples can be found in this jupyter notebook\n",
    "\n",
    "It is expected that simulator can perform following:\n",
    "   - Initalize state\n",
    "   - Read program, and for each gate:\n",
    "        - Calculate matix operator\n",
    "        - Apply operator (modify state)\n",
    "   - Perform multi-shot measurement of all qubits using weighted random technique\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Functions\n",
    "\n",
    "### initialize_qubits\n",
    "Initialize the ground state of the simulated quantum computer with an arbitrary size.\n",
    "\n",
    "- *Inputs*: \n",
    "    - (int) number of qubits in computer\n",
    "- *Output*: \n",
    "    - (1D array) vectors of size 2^n with a 1 in the first element\n",
    "    \n",
    "### get_circuit_operator\n",
    "Obtain the circuit operator $O$ for a given gate $U$ acting on target qubits $q$\n",
    "\n",
    "- *Inputs*: \n",
    "    - (int) Total number of qubits\n",
    "    - (2D array) Gate unitary\n",
    "    - (1D array) Target qubit(s) to apply gate\n",
    "- *Output*: \n",
    "    - (2D array) $2^n$x$2^n$ matrix operator\n",
    "   \n",
    "***Single Qubit Gate***\n",
    "\n",
    "   The single qubit gate is computed by the tensor product \n",
    "   $$ O = I\\otimes I\\otimes...\\otimes I\\otimes U \\otimes I....\\otimes I $$\n",
    "   where the length of the product is the total number of qubits and $U$ is placed in the q$^{th}$ position of the product.\n",
    "   \n",
    "***Multi-Qubit Gate***\n",
    "\n",
    "This function can compute the circuit operator for an arbitary controlled-$U$ gate.  This is done by the addition of two tensor products\n",
    "\n",
    "\begin{equation} O_1 = I\\otimes ... \\otimes I \\otimes \\ket{0}\\bra{0} \\otimes I \\otimes...\\otimes I \\otimes I...\\otimes I \end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "\begin{equation} O_2 = I\\otimes ... \\otimes I \\otimes \\ket{1}\\bra{1} \\otimes I \\otimes...\\otimes U \\otimes I...\\otimes I \end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ O = O_1 + O_2 $$\n",
    "where the projection operators $\\ket{0}\\bra{0}$ and $\\ket{1}\\bra{1}$ are at the *control* position of the product and $I$ and $U$ are applied in the *target* position of the product.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### run_program\n",
    "Function to run the quantum simulator and return the final output state.  The function will initialize the computer state and execute each of the gates to their target qubits in succession.\n",
    "- *Inputs*:\n",
    "    - (int) Number of qubits\n",
    "    - (dict) Program to execute\n",
    "        - The format of this input assumes a *dict* with keys \"gate\" containing an array of the gates to apply (assumes 2x2 for all gates), and \"target\" containing an array of qubits to apply the gates to.\n",
    "        - To implement a c$U$ gate, set the \"gate\" to the $U$ operator and the \"target\" to be [$q_c$,$q_t$] where $q_c$ is the control qubit index and $q_t$ is the target qubit index.  (Note, \"target\" is assumed to specify the target qubit starting at $0$.)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        - Example input \n",
    "        \n",
    "        { \"gate\":[ [[0.70710678, 0.70710678],[0.70710678, -0.70710678]], [[0,1],[1,0]] ], \"target\":[ [0], [1] ] }\n",
    "        \n",
    "- *Outputs*:\n",
    "    - (1D array) Final state after all circuit operators are applied from the program\n",
    "    \n",
    "    \n",
    "### measure_all\n",
    "Function which takes a weighted random measurement based on the input state given\n",
    "- *Inputs*:\n",
    "    - (1D array) State vector\n",
    "- *Outputs*:\n",
    "    - (int) Base$_{10}$ integer corresponding to the state which was selected by the weighted random measurement\n",
    "    \n",
    "    \n",
    "### get_bin\n",
    "Return the binary representation of a given integer\n",
    "- *Inputs*:\n",
    "    - (int) Number to be cast in binary\n",
    "    - (int) Number of bits to represent the number\n",
    "- *Outputs*:\n",
    "    - (string) Binary representation of input integer\n",
    "    \n",
    "\n",
    "### get_counts\n",
    "Perform a sequence of measurements on a given state and return the number of counts for each that state that was measured.\n",
    "- *Inputs*: \n",
    "    - (1D array) State to be measured\n",
    "    - (int) Number of qubits\n",
    "    - (int) Number of shots\n",
    "- *Outputs*:\n",
    "    - (dict) Dict containing \"state\" and total number of counts pairs\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### plot_histogram\n",
    "Plot a histogram of the outputted counts from a set of measurements\n",
    "- *Inputs*:\n",
    "    - (dict) Counts dict output from get_counts function\n",
    "- *Outputs*:\n",
    "    - (none) Does not return anything, prints a bar graph of the normalized counts"
   ]
